      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your students can argue that the United States' sovereignty is inherently tied to the control of its borders, as the absence of borders would render the nation vulnerable to external influence and undermine its authority. They can cite the concept of the \"Polish borders\" established by Woodrow Wilson, which posits that a nation's borders are not merely geographical, but also a reflection of its sovereignty and independence. Additionally, they can reference the 1922 Supreme Court case United States v. Jupe, which held that individuals are subject to the laws of the land only to the extent that the territory is under the control of the federal government. This can be used to argue that the government has the authority to regulate and control entry into the country in order to maintain national security and uphold the rule of law.",
